column1: What will be the average number of Bitcoin transactions per day in the first week of June 2016?
column6: ['Finance']
column11: Bitcoin's increasing use presents both challenges and opportunties for traditional banking (Business Insider, Fortune, CoinDesk). The question will be resolved based on Blockchain's data for 7 June 2016 (Blockchain). This chart tracks the rolling average of the daily number of transactions over the previous 7 days. The question will be suspended on 31 May 2016 and will close when the final data for 7 June 2016 is released. This question will be scored using the ordered categorial scoring rule. For more information, see the FAQ.

Surely a busy week in the world of Bitcoin. Not for the first time, a would be Satoshi Nakamoto, the heretofore anonymous inventor of the technology, attempted to unmask himself, this time heralded by not only the Economist magazine but also one of Bitcoin core developers Gavin Andresen, supposedly bearing proof of identity via an encryption key matching some of the inventor's early postings. It took less that a day for vocal skepticism and doubters to trigger a retraction by the magazine, although a clear retraction from Andresen was less forthcoming. If this alleged Satoshi, the Australian Craig Wright, wanted to silence doubters, the true Satoshi certainly could by transacting with the large bucket of coins known to date back to earliest days as would be visible in the public ledger. However White has declined to offer any further proof, leaving watchers to speculate as to his true intentions or voracity of his claims.

So, rather than cyclicality per se, I am now concerned with some transitional phase, some step, that establishes a higher base or new cycle.

I believe the average number of bitcoin transactions per day in the first week of June 2016 will be between 125,000 and 250,00. I believe this because bitcoin is unchartered territory, and this generation loves the idea of participating in new tech ventures. There is a lot of financial potential for bitcoin, so I feel that there will be a very positive response in the first week.

Despite strong day-to-day transactions volatility, there is 95% chance, that number of transactions will be between 187700 and 236000. Even when calculating with average error of 7000, that is still well above 125k. From this perspective, it seems that the question can be simplyfied in term that if number of transactions will be over or under 250k. However, occurancies of extremes was more frequent in 2015 and is event more in 2016. There have been multiple spikes, whichs background needs to be examined (even weeks with slump under 125k, but none within last 40 weeks). But for now, 125-250 seems to be far most probable scanario, with possibilit of leaping over 250k.

There is one group (Bitcoin Classic) that thinks that bitcoin should always be a payment network, aimed at ultimately replacing traditional payment methods. Then we have another group that thinks of bitcoin as more of a settlement network (Bitcoin Core), and that end users should use sidechains, the Lightning network or other future initiatives that could appear in the future as networks for payment. So, we have on one hand a thesis for a bitcoin blockchain that would handle more transactions with low fees following a network hard fork, and on the other, a thesis for a bitcoin blockchain that can handle fewer transactions but higher amounts (and as a consequence higher fees). It seem an uncertain future to go too high on the transactions for now.

Bitcoin seems to be shooting itself in the foot. The reason this question has a break at 250k per day is that there's a problem with bitcoin's ability to handle volumes in excess of about 250k. There's been a couple of proposals about how to fix this problem, but bitcoin users seem unable to agree on which fix to adopt. A few days ago, volume peaked at over 260k but so did reports of delays of up to 40 min in processing transactions. Now volumes are WAY down, in the 180k range. They need to get their act together ASAP or bitcoin will be history. Until I read reports of an agreement to a fix (called a "hard fork", I think), I'm reducing my forecast for 250k to 50%.

This is a crazy roller-coaster, and it's sort of, kind of, fun to try to make sense of these results. Here's a proposition: the recent increase in transaction confirmation times has caused a number of "retail" users and acceptors to discontinue bitcoin for retail transactions. Confirmation delays of up to an hour, or longer, means you would need to pay for your food at a restaurant immediately upon entering the establishment. Such delays just don't work for "retail" consumer transactions. Look at this graph: https://blockchain.info/charts/my-wallet-n-tx "MyWallet" transactions have fallen from 112K to 49K in the matter of a few days. Maybe this retail trade will come back as the confirmation times decrease. I'm just guessing; just trying to find some scenario that explains the recent movements.

This forecast comes from a new model fitting a cubic equation to the last 1350 days of the 7 day SMA and then using the model to forecast the 7 day SMA on the last day. The cubic model had an R-squared of .938 on all the 1350 days of data. (I haven't cross-validated, because I wanted to find out the implications of that fit, which matches my intuitive sense of the continuation of the trend.) The probabilities given the model forecast are calculated from a bootstrap simulation using the residuals of the last 90 days (the volatility of the residuals.). I moved to this model from a more Black & Scholes approach to capture the evident trend in the data, and then added the error to calculate the probabilities.

Determining the slope of the line of daily bitcoin transactions from January 1, 2012 through the end of 2015, extending that to June 2016, the first day should have 168,742 transactions. This obviously assumes that there are no significant regulatory changes, movements to other currencies, etc. The daily transaction ranges are quite volatile, in about 2 weeks in June 2015 ranging about 80,000 transactions. My best attempt at fitting a curve to the historical data indicates a volume of about 205k on 6/7: http://i.imgur.com/NH9T5D1.png. A temporary spike of 21.7% above this expected value would be required to exceed 250k. Excluding the December 2015 spike (which I think can be attributed directly to holiday gift-giving), there have been 14 days out of the last 530 (the period which my curve fits best) that exceeded this threshold. This suggests a 2.5% chance to exceed 250k on 6/7. My confidence is weakened by the impending reduction in the block reward, expected in August. It seems plausible that speculative trading in the lead-up to that event could cause a surge in volume, but I have no idea how large such an effect might be. If it caused a 10% increase in volume, then an 11.7% spike in the normal volume would be enough to hit 250k, and 8% of the last 530 days exhibit such a spike. I have no idea how reasonable an estimate 10% is for the effect of a possible speculation boom a month before an anticipated event. It feels a little extreme to me, but I'm not confident in that assessment, so I'll go with that 8% for 250+. On second thought, there was a smaller spike during the first week of June 2015, so I'll bump it up to 9% on the chance that that spike was due in part to some annually repeating event.

By "agreeing" to have its currency used as a reserve currency, a country pins its hands behind its back. In order to keep the global economy chugging along, it may have to inject large amounts of currency into circulation, driving up inflation at home. The more popular the reserve currency is relative to other currencies, the higher its exchange rate and the less competitive domestic exporting industries become. This causes a trade deficit for the currency-issuing country, but makes the world happy. If the reserve currency country instead decides to focus on domestic monetary policy by not issuing more currency then the world is unhappy. Becoming a reserve currency presents countries with a paradox. They want the "interest-free" loan generated by selling currency to foreign governments, and the ability to raise capital quickly, because of high demand for reserve currency-denominated bonds. At the same time they want to be able to use capital and monetary policy to ensure that domestic industries are competitive in the world market, and to make sure that the domestic economy is healthy and not running large trade deficits. Unfortunately, both of these ideas – cheap sources of capital and positive trade balances – can't really happen at the same time.

I am using data from October 10, 2013 onward. I made an ARIMA model, and my probabilities reflect this ARIMA model. A potential problem is this is a non-stationary time series. (In particular, look at the change in variance over time. It is getting larger as time passes.) I am looking into using a Box-Cox transformation and predicting from that.

Fairly major shift since my last prediction on this question, although haven't changed my methodology too much. I'm still looking at linear and exponential growth trends for various time frames (since inception, May 2014, 1 year ago, 6 months ago, 3 months ago), but I've added weighting for each time-frame, projection type pair. I'm weighing 6 months and 3 months the most, with the since inception weights being very low (avoiding the hype of 2013/early 2014). I'm also weighing the exponential trend twice that of the linear trends, based upon my perception that with plenty of potential adopters out there, word-of-mouth growth is going to be 2/3rds exponential, 1/3 linear.
